  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Competition</h3>
    <p>You work in a fast-paced, high-performance environment—and that can be both exciting and demanding. While some colleagues seem to have endless energy and always impress the boss, you're balancing a lot: family responsibilities, school events, surprise sick days, and more. It can feel like everyone else has it all together, while you’re doing your best to stay afloat. You're not alone—and there's a better way to thrive in this kind of environment.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Soft Skills</h3>
    <p>You chose a technical field because it played to your strengths—it felt natural, familiar, and rewarding. Along the way, your role expanded in exciting (and unexpected) ways: now you're leading teams, mentoring others, writing proposals, navigating client conversations, and stepping up at business events. These are valuable opportunities to grow—but no one handed you a manual. The good news? These skills can be learned, and they’ll take your impact to the next level.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Professional Development Options</h3>
    <p>Your industry is always evolving, and that means you're constantly expected to adjust—often with very little notice. New announcements, shifting priorities, and changing expectations can make it hard to catch your breath. While technical training is easy to find, developing the people-side of your role is a different story. Skills like communication, leadership, and presence aren’t often taught. But they can be learned—with the right guidance and a little practice.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Directions and Decisions</h3>
    <p>Your career can go in a variety of directions. You can become a business developer, a manager, or a technical guru, but you might have no idea which one is right for you. You might want to do only one, or two, but which ones? What if you want to do all three? What if your manager wants you to enter something you don't like?</p>
  </div>
  <div class="subs-item">
    <h3>Workplace Loneliness</h3>
    <p>In today’s workplace, it’s easy to feel isolated—especially in environments where every hour is billable. Many organizations emphasize individual performance, sometimes at the expense of connection. While the intent is often to minimize distractions, we sometimes lose sight of how vital collaboration and camaraderie are. People do their best work when they feel supported, seen, and connected to their team.</p>
